Inflation in Europe has derailed on food
Accelerated inflation, measured in the euro area, is mainly due to the rapid rise in food prices.
In November, the price increase in the 13 euro area countries was higher than forecast, after an inflation rate of 2.6 per cent in October, annual inflation of 3.1 per cent was recorded, said the European Community statistical office in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts only indicated 3 per cent, said Bloomberg.
Unlike the U.S., British and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the key interest rate by saying that lower interest rates, with rising commodity prices and falling unemployment rates, would lead to an inflationary spiral.
The ECB would like to keep the inflation rate below but close to two per cent.
According to one analyst, it is Catch 22 for the ECB: "we must dissuade" inflation in order to no longer have to intervene on this subject at a later date.
In Germany, the inflation rate of 3.3 per cent is a record in the last 12 years and in Spain it has risen from 3.6 to 4.1.
Inflation in the euro area took off because of the rapid rise in food and energy prices.
Grain futures market ratings have increased by 88 per cent and soybean prices have also reached their highest since 1973.
The price of food oil and dairy products also increased considerably in 2007.
This year, the world price of oil rose by 52 per cent and last month a barrel of black gold cost almost $100.
According to the ECB, in 2008 the inflation rate will rise from 2.1 per cent this year to 2.5 per cent, but in 2009 it will fall to 1.9 per cent.
According to analysts, the 12-month inflation rate remains around 3 percent, however, over the next 3-4 months, the annual average rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to reduce the key interest rate twice in 2008.
Gallup points to government crisis
After a long stagnation, the number of supporters of Fidesz (Alliance of Young Democrats) has increased significantly at the beginning of December. So since 2002, it currently has the largest number of supporters, while Gallup (Survey Institute) has never seen such low socialist support, i.e. 13 percent.
For the faithful voters, the difference would represent, due to the greater determination of the opposition voters, a support of more than two thirds (71 percent) against the support of a fifth (20 percent) for the MSZP (Hungarian Socialist Party).
According to the poll, the MDF (Hungarian Democratic Forum) and the SZDSZ (Alliance of Free Democrats) are below the parliamentary threshold: their support is two per cent throughout the population.
Of the loyal voters some went to vote, the number of supporters of both parties increased by 1 percent.
The economic climate has continued to deteriorate compared to the previous lowest point, the proportion of those who considered the country's economic situation to be particularly severe has never been higher, it amounts to 41 per cent and, according to 46 per cent, the situation is quite serious.
After the more optimistic outlook of last spring and summer, families are again more pessimistic about their financial situation.
Next year, the majority of the population anticipates an increase and only one-tenth anticipates an improvement in the situation.
Last December, 71 per cent of those surveyed, a majority never seen in previous Gallup polls, felt that the Prime Minister was doing his job rather badly than well.
13 percent of respondents have confidence or a lot of confidence in Ferenc Gyurcsány while 38 percent support Viktor Orbán.
54 per cent do not trust the Prime Minister at all and 27 per cent trust the President of Fidesz.
One of the indicators of change in the political situation is the proportion of society that believes that discontent with the Prime Minister can be dealt with without a change of government.
While after the riots of last October, 35 percent of respondents wanted the government and the Prime Minister to remain in office, at present this rate is only 20 percent. The relative majority (33 percent) believes that the holding of new elections would be the solution to this situation.
When asked about the intention to vote, 60 per cent of respondents said they would certainly vote and the additional 20 per cent said they would probably vote.
For comparison, for a "legislative election next Sunday", only 55 per cent of those polled would certainly participate and 15 per cent would probably participate. According to current intentions, the result of the referendum would be no doubt.
74 per cent of people would say no to higher education fees, 79 per cent would say no to consultation fees, and 84 per cent would say no to hospital fees.
When we look only at the same proportions among those who expressed their intention to vote in the referendum, 81, 84 and 89 per cent respectively would reject the introduction of registration fees, consultation fees and hospital living expenses.
Auchan is the most expensive, Tesco has increased its prices by almost twenty percent
The hypermarkets in the Budaörs trade triangle maintained the average price increase of 16 per cent last year, the difference being that this year the VAT rate did not increase.
Article by Napi Gazdaság (Daily Economy)
This year, in the commercial triangle of Budaörs, the usual daily Christmas Basket also increased by 16 per cent on average, a value increase of well over a thousand forints was displayed in all hypermarkets.
Prices, "which had already flown away" in the major food stores last December, have not risen sharply compared to the previous high base.
Nevertheless, consumers are obviously shocked to see that items purchased well below nine thousand forints last year now cost more than ten thousand forints.
The Daily Basket in the hypermarkets surveyed exceeded the psychological threshold of ten thousand forints by at least 91 forints.
And the highest value of the basket was 10,573 forints.
(In 2003, this value was 6,800 forints.)
Prices for Unicum and live fish remained almost at last year's level, but prices for turkey fillet, nuts and poppy rose sharply.
In stores, the price of flour and bread followed the data of the KSH (Central Institute of Statistics) but at Auchan, only 139 forints of bread were found.
Competition has not lowered the price of the product below 200 forints.
It was surprising to see, also in this hypermarket, that the price of the two-litre bottle of Coca-Cola was below 200 forints, so it only cost 257 forints the bottle included.
Nevertheless, this year, in terms of Daily Basket, Auchan was the most expensive and Cora the cheapest.
According to our calculations, Cora increased the price of its Daily Basket by 15 percent while Tesco and Auchan increased them by about 18 and 18 percent respectively.
By comparing last year's most expensive basket with this year's cheapest basket, we see a difference of 12 percent, while the difference between last year's cheapest and this year's most expensive basket is 21 percent.
Prices increased by an average of 1,480 forints.
Last year, prices rose by an average of 1,206 forints, while knowing that the impact of the increase in the VAT rate was already noticed in last year's Christmas prices.
This process has made trade perplexed, hypermarkets could not visibly determine what margin to apply to products as they were unable to predict the impact of price change on consumption.
(If a trader miscalculates the rotation of a product, he risks losing a big profit on the margin adapted to the intensity of the trade.)
Because of the change in the rate of VAT, the increase in the prices of the Daily Basket evolved so excessively that the most expensive basket was 1,720 forints higher than the value of the 2006 basket, while the difference between the cheapest baskets was only 844 forints.
This year, the difference was not so excessive since the value of the most expensive basket was 1,630 forints higher than last year and prices at the least increased by 1,284 forints as well.
By bringing the two Christmas seasons closer together, we have seen a catastrophic price increase, and in less than 20 months the prices of daily consumer items have increased by more than 30 percent in hypermarkets.
(This does not necessarily confirm the KSH data: for some essential supplies, the statistical institute has seen a price increase of more than 30 per cent in 12 months.
This is the case, for example, of flour and egg.)
According to the Daily Basket of the latter, this seems almost absurd since the price level of this product, already very expensive last year, has increased by just over 10 percent compared to the base.
According to the evidence, flour suppliers are in a stronger position than egg suppliers because they have succeeded in gaining acceptance of the sharp price increase also by multinationals.
In the commercial gold triangle, hypermarkets do not complain, they constantly record good years.
According to our experiences, the majority of customers no longer look at prices in the three hypermarkets visited.
They buy everything in quantity, they take long-storage food per pallet.
Wednesday morning important tails formed at the crates of the three hypermarkets as the number of customers increased sharply.
However, according to our information, the turnover is less significant in the provinces, many multinationals complain to the survey companies that they do not even reach the expected turnover, not only for food but also for sustainable consumer goods.
Many hospitals save money on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand infections, caused mainly by the incorrect use of antibiotics, have been registered in hospitals.
The hygienic conditions of hospitals, the insufficient number of beds, the overworking of medical personnel do not help to block infections, says the Chief Medical Officer of the National Epidemiology Centre.
Many hospitals are also saving on disinfectants
Not long ago an MRSA infection was diagnosed in the trauma department of János Hospital.
The antibiotic-resistant bacterium was detected on a man hospitalized following a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year a similar infection occurred in the same place.
The injured person in a serious car accident came out of the hospital but shortly after he had to return because of an MRSA infection and, since then, the doctors were unable to perform a major operation because of the bacteria in his body.
Until 10 December this year, 1,094 hospital infections generated by a multi-drug-resistant pathogen were reported to the National Nosocomial Surveillance System, said Karolina Böröcz, Chief Medical Officer of the National Epidemiology Centre.
To know that it is the number of infections caused by a multi-drug resistant pathogen that has actually been registered in hospitals and for the rest we have no information.
Approximately two-thirds of infections (683 infections) were caused by MRSA, i.e., methicillin-oxacillin-resistant staphylococcus aureus.
One third of people carry Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their noses without developing a disease.
Infections caused by SA (such as anginas, tonsillitis, skin infections, traumatic infections) respond well to antibiotics, they are easily cured.
However, if antibiotics are used excessively or inappropriately, the bacterium, which reacts well to antibiotics, will develop a bacteria that is well resistant to antibiotics that will proliferate rapidly in poor hospital conditions.
In case of temporary or prolonged malfunction of the immune system, this bacterium can cause serious hospital infections, such as traumatic infection or septicemia, on elderly patients, small weights or with a weakened organism.
According to the medical director of János hospital, there is nothing special about MRSA infections, these infections are part of the daily life of hospitals.
Above all, we must not confuse the infection with the epidemic, we do not find MRSA only where we do not look for them, said Tibor Nyulasi.
SAs are resistant to antibiotics.
"These patients are isolated, the health care staff wear rubber gloves and protective masks and we have antibiotics adapted to treat them," said Tibor Nyulasi.
A priori, hospitalized patients are examined if they carry MRSA, however infection cannot always be avoided.
Sample sampling is not in mode
The vast majority of infections caused by MRSA could be prevented, but current conditions and circumstances in Hungarian hospitals are not favourable to prevent the development and proliferation of multi-drug-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröcz.
As this infection occurs mainly in hospitals and seniors' homes, hospitals should monitor in-patients and immediately isolate patients with MRSA.
However, microbiological sampling is not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
It should be noted that the National Social Security Fund does not fund these examinations.
Most cases occur only if the MRSA infection is detectable on the patient, said the Chief Medical Officer of the Epidemiological Centre.
The European Union has rigorous recommendations for the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also Hungarian directives for the cure of certain infections and syndromes.
Efforts must be made to ensure that antibiotic therapy is targeted, i.e. microbiological examinations should be carried out to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always take this into account.
Microbiological sampling is even more rare in ambulatory and basic care, said Karolina Böröcz.
Many hospitals save money on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA proliferate from one patient to another most often through medical personnel.
It is therefore essential to wash your hands, put on gloves and protective masks. However, there are also significant deficiencies in hospitals in this area.
MRSA proliferate by inhalation of droplets and contact. However, due to conditions in Hungarian hospitals, the infected patient cannot always be isolated.
In addition, rooms are often full, beds are often too close to each other, while in terms of epidemics, patients should be at least 1.5 metres away from each other.
Unfortunately, we also see that hospitals, in a difficult financial situation, are saving on disinfectants, they lack nurses, there are many patients, so the risk of contamination is even greater, said Karolina Böröcz.
According to Karolina Böröcz, in hospitals or preventive measures, the number of infections is lower in a demonstrable way or the proliferation of the pathogen can be blocked.
Government project against MRSA
Treatment of MRSA infection is an exorbitant expense for social security funds, which is why this infection is being combated everywhere.
In England, for example, the government has established a program to prevent or reduce the incidence of ASM.
According to published data, this program is effective and MRSA infections are showing a decreasing trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) identifies as one of its priorities the prevention of the incidence of multi-drug-resistant pathogens (such as MRSAs) and the prevention of hospital infections caused by these pathogens.
The commissioner, who was responsible for a fatal accident, was not intoxicated.
The official finding concerning the fatal accident caused by the commissioner of the 22nd district was drawn up.
It may be excluded that the commissioner of the 22nd arrondissement, who has resigned from his post since then, who crushed a pedestrian by causing his death last Tuesday, would have led to a state of intoxication or stunned, communicated Friday Attila Morvai, spokesman of the Public Prosecutor's Office of the capital after the relative finding was established.
The finding confirmed the first result of the investigation, which has already found that the former Commissioner did not drink alcohol before driving.
Last Tuesday, the former head of the 22nd district police station crushed a 55-year-old man who was facing him when he shot, with his personal car, in Kossuth Lajos Street in the 22nd district. The man wanted to cross the road by not passing through the pedestrian crossing.
(In fact, the fact that he was crossing the road outside the pedestrian crossing is not a mitigating circumstance, according to the Highway Code, a car that starts a turn must let pedestrians pass.)
The pedestrian died after being taken to the hospital.
As a result of this accident, the Commissioner resigned from his post and requested his retirement because, according to police communication, this accident greatly upset him.
The investigation into this case is carried out by the Public Prosecutor's Office in Budapest.
Attila Morvai also mentioned that the former Commissioner cooperated from the beginning with the magistrates responsible for conducting the investigation.
Additional EUR 400 million for infrastructure
Hungary's Minister of Finance János Veres and Vice-President Marta Gajecka of the European Investment Bank (EIB) signed three EUR 400 million agreements in Budapest on a credit line to support education, transport and environment infrastructure and energy.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) adopted a budget of EUR 300 million for the Hungarian budget financing of transport and environment projects to be carried out from the Cohesion Fund, of which a credit contract worth EUR 100 million has already been signed by the parties.This time, the contract signed concerns the use of the remaining EUR 200 million.
The agreement on the appropriation of EUR 150 million also covers the budgetary financing of education-related projects.
The EIB has approved a total of EUR 300 million for Hungary, while the remaining EUR 150 million can be used later following the extension of the credit agreement.
The parties have signed a €50 million contract for innovation, the state budget will use this envelope in the first place as part of the research and development project to be carried out at the University of Debrecen.
During the negotiations, the metro line 4 project was also discussed.
The parties agreed that they would discuss the possible modification of the original contract once Hungary has finalized the details of the financing of the metro with the EU.
According to János Veres, this could be done in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has provided a total of EUR 8.4 billion for the financing of 113 projects in Hungary.
The EIB grants its loans at the EURIBOR-linked interest rate, with a grace period of 8 years and no commitment commission.
Bulgaria, the paradise of the EU real estate market
The evolution of the Bulgarian real estate market is spectacular, the attention of the whole of Europe is turned to this Balkan country little cited in the past.
What, or who is bought in this EU market that is always the cheapest but will quickly become expensive?
Analysis of the Bulgarian division of Re/Max.
Currently, in real estate, Bulgaria is undoubtedly the most popular target in Eastern Europe with its ski apartments and houses by the cheap sea.
In the mountains, the most popular regions are Bansko, Borovec, Pambrovo and Vitosa and, by the sea, Albena, the "Golden Sands", the "Sun Coast", the former Sozopol and Nessebar but more and more of them are looking for a building in the Kavarna and Balcik region as well.
According to the analysts of Re/Max Bulgaria, sooner or later, the central region of the country, namely Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna, will also arouse the interest of investors and they are also more and more to buy in the very cheap corner of Ruse.
Sofia, the capital city, also offers attractive opportunities, with commercial and office space promising the highest depreciation rate.
Bulgaria is on the best track to become one of the most attractive golf paradises in Europe and thus be a priority destination, after the summer and winter seasons, also in the other two seasons of the year.
The more vigilant investors are already buying in large numbers, for example in the corner of Bansko.
According to analysts, people buying a building in Bulgaria are at the same time seeking to change their lives, their way of life.
Most buyers are English, but others come from France, Belgium, Spain and more and more from Romania.
Maltese and Cypriot investors are also present. Along the Black Sea and in the most famous ski resorts, we traditionally meet many Russian buyers.
Foreign buyers are divided into three groups, says Georgij Jankov, Regional Director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
People who intend to settle in buy renovated buildings, at a price ranging from 50 to 100 thousand euros, or old dilapidated houses, at a price ranging from 5 to 15 thousand euros, which are then renovated.
The criteria are easy access and communication possibilities, proximity to a large city, shops and, in general, that of the local doctor.
The second group includes buyers of second homes (since last December Bulgaria has been listed as one of the top 10 holiday destinations in Germany).
The third group is made up of commercial investors who buy in the hope of achieving medium- or long-term added value.
The price of capital buildings is constantly rising as a result of increasing demand.
In the European Union, real estate prices are the lowest in Bulgaria. However, over the last 5 years, they have increased by 21 per cent each year.
The increase in real estate prices mainly exceeds the increase in wages.
Fodor and the six percent Hungarian
According to the communication of Gábor Fodor, Minister of the Environment and Waters, the meetings of professionals end Tuesday, yet Wednesday, after the official opening, the negotiations of ministers on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world will discuss the Bali Road Map, which is supposed to define the efforts to be made after the Kyoto Protocol's emission reduction period until 2012.
At the moment, there are intense discussions on this issue between developing and developed countries.
The United States also reported that, for the time being, it did not wish to discuss exact figures, although it was prepared to sign an agreement to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25 to 40 per cent from 1990 levels by 2020.
Another important topic of the conference is whether developed countries commit themselves, excluding emission reductions, to providing financial and technological assistance to countries in need.
An agreement has also been signed on aid to developing countries.
The Kyoto Protocol aid fund will be managed by a 16-member board of directors, probably under the UN Global Environment Fund (GEF), reported Piac es Profit (Market and Profit).
The six percent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, Environment and Water Minister Gábor Fodor confirms the EU's ambition to retain its role as a flagship in global efforts to protect the climate and encourage the signing of the new international agreement before 2009.
The Minister explained that the EU was committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 per cent by 2020 compared to the level reached in 1990, regardless of the success of the signing of the "Post-2012 Agreement", and was prepared to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by up to 30 per cent if the other major regions of the world and/or developing countries were also prepared to make commitments appropriate to their responsibilities and capabilities.
Gábor Fodor recalled that in 1997 the Kyoto Protocol countries had achieved a total reduction of 5.2 per cent and all 15 EU members at that time made the commitment of 8 per cent less.
Hungary has made a commitment to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6 per cent compared to the period 1985-87, and our country will fulfil its commitment, recalls the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
The challenge is great in Bali because the long-term international agreement on climate policy must be put in place within two years, otherwise the entry into force of the agreement would certainly be postponed after 2012. In this case, the commitments to reduce below the Kyoto Protocol values would not be immediately followed by a new international system for reducing emissions, the need for which was stressed in the new report of IPCC, an international scientific body, which won the UN Nobel Peace Prize for dealing with climate change.
The reduction in emissions would be delayed and the increase in the Earth's average temperature by more than 2 degrees celcius could no longer be avoided which, according to scientists, would have extremely serious and irrevocable consequences.
British Army recruits on YouTube
The British Army units communicate on the video-sharing site recordings made during its operations in Iraq and Afghanistan with the aim of becoming popular.
First of all, it was the British Air Force (RAF) that was passionate about YouTube: the special units operating in Afghanistan are loading video footage of operations against the Taliban since March 2006, announced the BBC.
These recordings, taken with miniature cameras mounted on the helmet, are checked at the headquarters of the air force operations in Kandahar and then transferred to Londres where the compatriots charge them on the Internet.
The political message is inescapable
Air Force soldiers have already passed 139 sequences online through this route and their "chain" has been watched by more than 75 thousand people.
The British Ministry of Defence registered under the name "defenceheadquarters" in the spring of 2007 and released videos on operations in Iraq and Afghanistan, while the Commonwealth Ministry (Commonwealth Office) and the international peacekeeping forces in Iraq (MNFI) also have their own channels on YouTube.
Mission to Afghanistan
According to the initial objective of the air force, the videos were posted on the Internet to recruit, and according to the Ministry of Defence, they were also used to publicize to the general public the real objectives of the army's presence abroad.
Propaganda published in this way costs almost nothing compared to the usual advertising of recruitment on television, communicated to the BBC Gordon Mackenzie, a defence consultant. On the other hand, it inevitably carries a political message as it justifies in a special form the soundness of the military operations decided by the government.
The Americans made a game.
The army is annoyed because, apart from the videos composed and censored carefully, amateur videos have passed on to the sharing site which also present, for example, the deaths of soldiers: in the "official" propaganda films, a little hypocritical, the officers do not avoid talking about the losses but they never present the bloody side of the fight.
In fact, many videos had already been posted on the Internet showing the areas of operation in Iraq and Afghanistan that were being carried out on a real mission, but the British army has only recently been busy loading these videos.
Americans do the recruitment a little differently by using the free downloadable America's Army Shooting Game. In this game the player can put himself directly in place of the soldiers as part of a more or less real simulation.
