The party is not marked in red everywhere
In Hungary, the law defines exactly the holidays and, around the holidays, it has become common practice to reorganise working days, the number of which will decrease next year.
Parties are not uniform in the EU and the United States either.
Hungarian legislation distinguishes between national and state holidays and rest days.
Days of rest are often linked to religious holidays or important historical events.
In Hungary, we celebrate the New Year, the last day of the year that ends and the first day of the New Year are also days of rest, the latter all the more so that New Year's Evers can rest quietly.
Moreover, in one year we have a total of eleven festivals marked in red.
March 15 is a national holiday, in commemoration of the revolution of 1848, as is October 23, which is also the memorial day of the revolution of 1956.
On August 20, we celebrate the constitution of our state, May 1 is Labour Day, and on November 1 and 2, we remember our dead family and friends.
In addition, we have two days at Easter, Pentecost and Christmas.
The days of our state holidays, national or religious rarely falling on a weekend, according to the calendar, it has become common to reorganize the working days in cases where there is only one working day before or after the feast marked in red.
It is true that we pay the price for extended weekends by working or going to school the Saturday before the extended weekend.
For many years, the Minister of Labour has made special regulations on the replacement days of the days preceding or following the holidays.
The Act extends to all employers and their employees, to civil servants and to persons working in the public service.
However, it does not apply to service companies, with institutions rotating continuously and in service, because of their vocation, and also for days of rest.
This year, the working days will be changed only around the end-of-year holidays: from December 24th, life almost stops all over the country because according to experiences the majority of people do more overtime or take vacations that they have saved for these purposes so that they can spend the days between Christmas and New Year's Day at home.
Next year many holidays fall in the middle or at the end of the week, so there will be fewer changes in working days compared to this year.
The calendar will be reorganized for the first time around the Labour Day to allow employees to stay at home four days in a row.
Saturday 25 April will be a day of work to have a day of rest on Friday 2 May.
Another change is scheduled for October 23rd: Saturday, October 18th will be a replacement working day on Friday 24.
On the other hand, next year, the end of the year promises to be marked by the holidays because from 24 December, everyone will take a non-stop break even if the New Year's Day falls on a Wednesday.
