Spectacular repair on space station
It took more than seven hours of space work for astronaut Scott Parazynski and his crewmates at the International Space Station (ISS) to perform the spectacular repair of a torn solar panel, essential for the continuation of the station's scientific activities.
A risky release that has accumulated records because of its duration, its remoteness from habitable modules, the speed with which it was conceived, tools "crafted" by astronauts to carry out the repair.
The problem appeared on Tuesday when the astronauts had unloaded the Harmony module from the Shuttle Discovery, a large cylindrical part that soon hosted the European and Japanese scientific laboratories (see box).
This module is a kind of dock for laboratory modules.
But we must be able to supply them with electricity.
The crew's second task was therefore to move a 17.5-tonne solar panel power generation module, already present on the ISS, to put it on its final position.
After moving it, the crew began the redeployment of the module's solar panels, which have a wingspan of 76 metres.
And that's where one of the panels, which unfold like accordions, was damaged about a metre by a cable that got stuck.
The deployment was stopped so as not to further damage the panel.
The astronauts, who were originally to perform a shuttle Discovery control exit and then go to repair another solar panel with a defective rotation system, were forced to devote themselves to the damaged panel.
And it was Scott Parazynski who was chosen to caracole at the end of the 30 meters length of the remote control arm of the shuttle added to that of the station to carry out the repair.
It is one of the best "spacewalker" of the Nasa.
Large, resistant, very skillful, he has a very developed torso and long arms.
At 46 years of age, this trained doctor was therefore given the task of "operating" the "injured" solar panel.
After precisely inspecting the damage, he severed the wrong cable and installed some kind of "clamps" on the damaged area.
He was assisted by a second "spacewalker" who remained near the airlock and, from the inside, by other astronauts, including Peggy Whitson, the crew commander.
The tool he used, a hockey mini-cane wrapped in insulation to avoid electrocution on solar panels producing several hundred volts, was designed and "briccoled" by astronauts aboard the station.
Once the operation was complete, Scott Parazynski waited until the panel was fully deployed before making an inventory of his tools and returning to the station interior.
Yesterday afternoon, astronauts enjoyed half a day of relaxation before today, seven astronauts returned to Shuttle Discovery for a return to Earth scheduled for Wednesday.
