They're not Warhols' cases.
The one who connects the Swedish concepts and wooden case, thinks of Ikea, but not Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
At the moment, wooden boxes made in Sweden cast shadows on Warhol's list of works.
A large part of the ninety Brillo-Boxes of "Stockholm Type" listed there are counterfeits.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" doubted a few months ago the authenticity of Andy Warhol's 1968 Brillo-Boxes, the internal research of the Moderna Museet in Stockholm today leads to a disenchanting result: the six "Brillo-Boxes", which the former director of the Pontus Hulten museum donated in 1995 to the Moderna Museet, are copies - as well as a large part of the other hundreds of Brillo-Boxen of "Stockholm Type", which circulate on the international art market.
Ancient history is entangled, a disconcerting chain of artistic and curatoric productions.
In 1964 Warhol created his first "Brillo-Boxes" in New York, painted wooden boxes based on the blue-white red design of the "Brillo" powdered soap cartons.
An exhibition of his work at the Moderna Museet presented in 1968 - with Warhol's agreement - hundreds of cases made of carton: These did not come (for financial reasons) from Warhol, but had been delivered directly from the carton factory Brillo.
These were not works of art, but rather their models, exhibition samples.
At the same time, Warhol had given permission in 1968 to produce a few wooden boxes in Brillo in Sweden, which were not in fact exposed to the Moderna Museet.
Witnesses of the time speak today of about fifteen wooden boxes that at the time would have entered by right into the history of art and auctions, as the original Brillo-Boxes of Andy Warhol authorized, with the name "Stockholm Type".
Some of them have reached more than $100,000 in auction sales.
The problem now is that the legendary director of the Pontus Hulten museum wrongly claimed that about one hundred wooden boxes had been produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol would then have given to him.
In fact, Hulten's 105 cases were produced in Malmö in 1990 alone, for an exhibition in St Petersburg.
At that time, Warhol had already been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, chief curator of the Moderna Museet, examined, next to the museum's six Brillo-Boxes, three other Swedish private collections, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their laminated panels were first printed and sanded, and then a white oil paint brush was applied.
The texture of the copies dating back to 1990 reveals, on the contrary, that the paint was directly applied without a background layer on the laminated panels, using a roll of paint - moreover, it is not an oil paint, but an acrylic.
"These crates were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo-Boxes," suggests Moderna Museet Director Lars Nittve: "If the 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' in New York does not come up with another decision, the Moderna Museet will classify the six crates in its collection as copies/exhibition material."
Already in July the Authentication Board announced, of course, that it would investigate the "heavy accusations" that will be raised in the case of powdered soap cases.
But since then we've had an inexorable silence there.
